Review: I don’t like what Disney did to one of my favorite books when I was younger. I’m disappointed. However, deep down I know this would happen. My 2014-year-old self, though, is pissed off!

No matter how cheesy or overdramatic this film may be, you can’t deny the superb artistry that’s present here! I can hear every footstep, I can feel the raindrops on my skin. This is just 46 minutes, and I’m left yearning for more.
I’m here because of Ji Chang Wook hahaha

The film opens with a cool, unearthly music hinting its offbeat feel early on. Two people fall in love at first sight; One disappears without warning; Two years and a bit, she’s with someone who looks exactly like him; Five more years, and someone reappears. On top of everything, it’s the well-sheened cinematography of Yasuyuki Sasaki which deserves the highest praise. It evokes a poetic and enigmatic aura of some kind out of the film’s neatly framed creams and beiges. …
Furrowed brows all over!! Two stars are for Mylene Dizon. She’s a stunner!

Tetsuya Nakashima’s ‘Confessions’ opens with a class of rowdy 13-year-old students sipping and slurping cartons of milk while their mild-mannered and soft-spoken teacher talks in front of them. This is artistically done through intercutting slow-mo insert shots of typical students: sleeping and daydreaming, texting, applying makeup, throwing papers and balls, chatting. The teacher then announces her resignation. Silence ensues, but only for a meager moment. Students get back to their own businesses, but the teacher still continues her monologue, and this…
